04180nam a22005295i 9780520913486DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19931993cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209134867 a10.1525/97805209134862doi  a(DE-B1597)519837  a(OCoLC)42922668  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ684b.A25 1993eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a306.872/0951/090212201 aEbrey, Patricia Buckley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Inner Quarters :bMarriage and the Lives of Chinese Women in the Sung Period /cPatricia Buckley Ebrey. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1993] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD -- tPREFACE -- tNOTES ON CONVENTIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tONE. Separating the Sexes -- tTWO. Meanings of Marriage -- tTHREE. Making a Match -- tFOUR. Rites and Celebrations -- tFIVE. Dowries -- tSIX. Upper-Class Wives as Inner Helpers -- tSEVEN. Women's Work Making Cloth -- tEIGHT. Husband-Wife Relations -- tNINE. Motherhood -- tTEN. Widowhood -- tELEVEN. Second Marriages -- tTWELVE. Concubines -- tTHIRTEEN. Continuing the Family Through Women -- tFOURTEEN. Adultery, Incest, and Divorce -- tFIFTEEN. Reflections on Women, Marriage, and Change -- tNOTES -- tSOURCES CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Sung Dynasty (960-1279) was a paradoxical era for Chinese women. This was a time when footbinding spread, and Confucian scholars began to insist that it was better for a widow to starve than to remarry. Yet there were also improvements in women's status in marriage and property rights. In this thoroughly original work, one of the most respected scholars of premodern China brings to life what it was like to be a woman in Sung times, from having a marriage arranged, serving parents-in-law, rearing children, and coping with concubines, to deciding what to do if widowed.Focusing on marriage, Patricia Buckley Ebrey views family life from the perspective of women. She argues that the ideas, attitudes, and practices that constituted marriage shaped women's lives, providing the context in which they could interpret the opportunities open to them, negotiate their relationships with others, and accommodate or resist those around them.Ebrey questions whether women's situations actually deteriorated in the Sung, linking their experiences to widespread social, political, economic, and cultural changes of this period. She draws from advice books, biographies, government documents, and medical treatises to show that although the family continued to be patrilineal and patriarchal, women found ways to exert their power and authority. No other book explores the history of women in pre-twentieth-century China with such energy and depth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMarriagexHistoryxChina. 0aMarriagezChinaxHistory. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsxChina. 0aWomenzChinaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520913486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520913486.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles